Workaround:
There are several potential workarounds for this issue.Workaround 1: Create an array or a cell array and store the contents of the individual variables as elements in that array or cell array. Rather than creating individual variables x1, x2, x3, ... you can create one variable and store data in its elements. As an example:% Instead of creating many individual variablesfor k = 1:10    eval(['x' num2str(k) ' = k;'])end% and extracting the contents of the third variabley = eval('x3')% Create one variable and use indexed assignment to fill itx = zeros(1, 10);for k = 1:10    x(k) = k;end% and extract the contents of the third elementy = x(3)If the contents of the individual variables are nonscalar but are the same size and data type, you can store them as rows, columns, or pages of an array:M = magic(4);for k = 1:4    eval(['y' num2str(k) ' = M.^k;']);endy = repmat(M, [1 1 4]);for k = 1:4    y(:, :, k) = M.^k;endisequal(y3, y(:, :, 3))If the contents of the individual variables are nonscalar and do not have the same size and/or data type, you can store them as the elements of a cell array. Note that to extract the contents of an element in a cell array, you need to use curly braces to index into the cell array.for k = 1:10    eval(['z' num2str(k) ' = ones(k);']);endz = cell(1, 10);for k = 1:10    z{k} = ones(k);endisequal(z8, z{8})Workaround 2: Store the data in the fields of a struct array using dynamic field name referencing. If the names you are using to create the individual variables provide important information about the contents of the variable, you can create a struct array with fields that use those names and contain the information you would have included in the individual variable. For example:% Store a user-entered age into a variable with a user-entered namename1 = input('Please enter your name:  ', 's');eval([name1 'Age = input(''Please enter your age:  '');'])fprintf('%s is %g years old.

', name1, eval([name1 'Age']));% Store a user-entered age into a struct using a user-entered field namename2 = input('Please enter your name:  ', 's');ages.(name2) = input('Please enter your age:  ');fprintf('%s is %g years old.

', name2, ages.(name2));Workaround 3: If you are using LOAD without any output arguments to read in a MAT-file containing many variables, call LOAD with a struct array output argument. This will LOAD in the variables from the MAT-file into fields of the output argument rather than as many individual variables. You can then use dynamic field names (as described in Workaround 2) to access the variables.% Create a MAT-file with 100000 variablesclear S;for k = 1:100000  S.(sprintf('x%d', k)) = k;endsave myfile.mat -struct Sclear S;% Attempt to load the variables from the fileload myfile.mat;% Load the variables into the fields of a struct arrayS2 = load('myfile.mat');Workaround 4: If your work involves processing a number of items (files, directories, etc.) and you are creating individual variables to use as temporary storage for each item, create a function that accepts an item and processes that item, then call the function for each item. Doing this will mean that the temporary variable is created in the workspace of the function and will be cleared after the function has finished processing each item.% Call the item-processing function% for each .jpg file in the current directoryfunction results = processAllImagesD = dir('*.jpg');results = zeros(1, numel(D));for k = 1:numel(D)  results(k) = processAnImage(D(k).name);end% This function operates on each item in turnfunction y = processAnImage(imageFilename)X = imread(imageFilename);temporaryData = sum(X(:));y = sum(X(:).^2)./temporaryData;
